{"award_age":70.0,"bio_image":"full\/20bd6294c07ec55ba4c400117e22d520319ae3ef.jpg","category":"Chemistry","country":"United Kingdom","date_of_birth":"1897-11-09T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"1978-06-07T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/en\/4\/44\/Ronald_George_Wreyford_Norrish.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ronald_George_Wreyford_Norrish","mini_bio":"<p><b>Ronald George Wreyford Norrish<\/b> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Fellow_of_the_Royal_Society\" title=\"Fellow of the Royal Society\" class=\"mw-redirect\">FRS<\/a><sup id=\"cite_ref-frs_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ronald_George_Wreyford_Norrish#cite_note-frs-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> (9 November 1897 \u2013 7 June 1978) was a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/United_Kingdom\" title=\"United Kingdom\">British<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Chemist\" title=\"Chemist\">chemist<\/a>. He was born in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cambridge\" title=\"Cambridge\">Cambridge<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/England\" title=\"England\">England<\/a>, and attended The <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Perse_School\" title=\"Perse School\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Perse School<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Emmanuel_College,_Cambridge\" title=\"Emmanuel College, Cambridge\">Emmanuel College, Cambridge<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-emmanuel_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ronald_George_Wreyford_Norrish#cite_note-emmanuel-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He was a former student of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Eric_Rideal\" title=\"Eric Rideal\">Eric Rideal<\/a>. Norrish was a prisoner for part of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/World_War_I\" title=\"World War I\">World War I<\/a> (1914\u20131918) and later commented, with sadness, that many of his contemporaries and potential competitors at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Cambridge\" title=\"University of Cambridge\">Cambridge<\/a> had not survived the War.<\/p><p>Norrish rejoined Emmanuel College as a Research Fellow in 1925 and later became the Head of the Physical Chemistry Department at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Cambridge\" title=\"University of Cambridge\">University of Cambridge<\/a>, occupying part of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Lensfield_Road\" title=\"Lensfield Road\">Lensfield Road<\/a> Building with the separate department 'Chemistry' (which encompassed organic, theoretical and inorganic chemistry). Both departments had separate administrative, technical and academic personnel until they merged to form one chemistry department under Sir <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_Meurig_Thomas\" title=\"John Meurig Thomas\">John Meurig Thomas<\/a> FRS in the early 1980s. Norrish researched photochemistry using continuous light sources (including after the 1945 war, searchlights). As a result of the development of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Flash_photolysis\" title=\"Flash photolysis\">flash photolysis<\/a>, he was awarded the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Chemistry\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Chemistry\">Nobel Prize in Chemistry<\/a> in 1967 along with <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Manfred_Eigen\" title=\"Manfred Eigen\">Manfred Eigen<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/George_Porter\" title=\"George Porter\">George Porter<\/a> for their study of extremely fast chemical reactions.<sup id=\"cite_ref-emmanuel_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Ronald_George_Wreyford_Norrish#cite_note-emmanuel-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> One of his accomplishments is the development of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Norrish_reaction\" title=\"Norrish reaction\">Norrish reaction<\/a>.<\/p>","name":"Ronald George Wreyford Norrish","place_of_birth":"Cambridge ,  England","place_of_death":"Cambridge ,  England","text":"Ronald George Wreyford Norrish , Chemistry, 1967","year":1967.0}